    "In the second case study, 252 items were identified, including 128 unique items and their duplicates.",
    "Among the 128 items, 76 were categorized as tools or objects, while 52 could not be classified in either tool or object category.",
    "In the third case study, 140 items were identified, with 81 unique items and their duplicates.",
    "Out of the 81 items, 47 were classified as tools or objects, while 34 could not be classified according to TRIZ.",
    "It is important to note that the elements of functional analysis for the first case study were not identifiable in the published version of the report, preventing the calculation of the comprehensiveness rate for the generation of functional analysis in this particular case study."
